title: For Sale/Trade:  Early 1980s Smith & Wesson 686 .357 mag Revolver 4 inch
postcontent:
Early 1980s Smith and Wesson 686 Revolver. 1983 I think. 4 inch barrel.  
This is among the most desirable of the 686s: it has solid machined trigger and hammer, firing pin is on the hammer, beautiful finish on all parts, super smooth trigger action, the classic locking system. The only thing it doesn't have is a recessed cylinder--which they only made on a few 686s. In other words, this is a better firearm than a brand new S&W 686.  Operating in single action, you only have to think about squeezing the trigger and the gun goes off. And that is without any custom work (which can easily be done on this revolver; more recent 686s do not have the quality of triggers and cannot be customized as well). It shoots straight, of course. I'm not a great shot and I regularly put 6 shot groups within a 50 cent piece at 25 feet with this gun.  It comes with classic S&W wood grips. Two leather holsters are included. 

Here's the story behind this 686:

This gun was given to me 7 months ago by my father in law. He acquired it in the early 80s right as he quit hunting. So it served as a home defense weapon--and just sat there for 30+ years.  I doubt he put a hundred rounds through it (partly because I've known him since the late 80s and I've only seen him fire the gun twice--with me, at my urging, and partly because he gave me two half full ancient ammo boxes along with the gun).  Since I acquired it I've shot almost 500 rounds (85% of which were .38s). 

It's a lovely gun. I just don't really like the ergonomics of the S&W as much as I do other pistols. 

Please email with questions. 
More pictures are here.

title: For Sale:  1945 Winchester M1 Carbine
postcontent:
I never shoot it, I feel bad that she just sits in the safe, so here she is. This is my 1945 Winchester M1 Carbine. Everything on the rifle is correct for a Winchester, has the Winchester markings such as the "W" in all of the right places. 

On the stock, the correct cartouches are present, the stock is the right "type IV" stock. In the pictures, you should be able to see the cartouches pretty clearly on the handguard and the stock itself inside the sling well. 

All of the metals are Winchester and proofed as such. The only discrepancy on this entire rifle is the bolt. Some people say it should have a round blued bolt, some say a round parkerized, some say a flat bolt. So, since I can't find anywhere that is 100% on the issue, I consider it correct because the patina on the bolt I have matches the receiver 100%. I'm in the military and can clearly tell you through observation that we almost never match things up identically and constantly mix things up and just "roll" with it. Besides, no one here (or so I assume) was with the rifle when it was built so no one knows for sure. The oiler bottle has the correct markings for a Winchester WWII circa and is original, not reproduction. 

The rifle comes with all magazines pictured. Some have markings, some don't. Some are USGI, and some I couldn't tell you for sure. There are 9x 15-rounders and 2x 30-rounders. If I come across more they will be tossed in. The sling is about all that isn't "correct" as it is a Korean marked sling, again, this rifle could have been used during the Korean War for all I know. 

Anyways, I have quite a bit consumed into this Carbine, I've had to acquire a few parts to "correct it" to where it is. If you want a beautiful carbine that has a beautiful stock, here's your chance. I'm a fan of originals so I had to have a Winchester since they did produce the first carbines. I'm asking $1500 for the Winchester with everything pictured. I feel that's reasonable. If not, I'm not in a hurry to sell and keeping this wouldn't be an issue. I appreciate everyone's time in reading this!

title: For Sale:   Lifted 1998 Jeep XJ 4x4
postcontent:
1998 Jeep Cherokee Classic XJ in very good condition with about 150k miles. Almost no rust, underbody and enginebay are extremely clean. What rust it did have has been treated and filled. The bottom half of it has been coated in bedliner to protect it from the salts in the winter. It has power leather front seats, power windows/locks, keyless remotes, etc. Interior is kept very clean with no weird smells or anything. I shampoo every new car I get, and am meticulous about keeping them clean. Everything works. It shifts into 4wd very smoothly, and will get you out of almost anything. Last winter during the major snow storms, it was the only vehicle in the neighborhood that could get it self out of the snow and down the road before the plows could get the couple feet of snow cleared. I've never been able to get it stuck, but the winch is there if it ever does.

It has the following aftermarket/custom/replaced parts:

- 4.5 inch rough country suspension lift
- 30'' tires on stock wheels, as well as a second set of black steel offroad wheels
- Warn front bumper (900 new)
- Warn driving lights(1200-1400 new)
- Badland winch
- Pioneer bluetooth head unit w/new speakers
- Husky floor mats(great for the mud/winters)
- Custom rear bumper w/tire carrier and full size spare
- K&N cold air intake(300 new)
- Brand new windshield
- Bushwacker fender flares (Not installed. Holes are drilled for them to mount to, but filled with rivets. Easy enough to remove the rivets and bolt on the flares if you like.)
- Etc

There are probably a few things I'm forgetting about.

Only con is that it pulls slightly to the left, and I haven't been able to figure out why. It doesn't really effect drivability too much though, and I drove it every day over the winter without any issues. No death wobble or anything that XJ's are notorious for.

I am asking $3500, but I would really like to trade for a 4x4 truck. I love my XJ's(this is my second), but I need a truck. I really like Toyota Pickups, or anything else interesting. Let me know if you have any questions, want to see it, or just want to throw me an offer. I'm willing to discuss any reasonable offers.

title: For Sale:  Ruger LCP .380
postcontent: The lightweight, compact design of the Ruger® LCP® Semi-Auto Pistol make it an ideal concealed carry gun, that's comfortable to carry all day, and quick to deploy. The LCP utilizes a double-action only, hammer-fired mechanism, with the hammer recessed into the rear of the slide to prevent snagging. The double-action only firing mode makes it simple to use in stressed situations—no levers or switches to remember—just point and shoot. The LCP features low profile front and rear sights integrated onto the slide that do not snag on clothing when pistol is drawn from a concealed position, and all sharp edges have been eliminated on the LCP to aid in concealment and to reduce wear on clothing. This LCP model features an alloy steel slide with a blued finish. Right-handed shooters can comfortably reach the magazine release on the LCP with their thumb, while left-handed shooters have no problem using their trigger finger. The mag release pushes in easily, but not so easily that the magazine pops out unexpectedly. Unlike many small semi-automatic pistols that operate with a blowback action, the Ruger LCP operates on a locked-breech system, which mitigates recoil and does not necessitate the user to pull the slide back against an excessively heavy recoil spring during loading. The LCP also has a manual slide hold-open latch for inspection and cleaning. The Ruger LCP is a well-designed, reliable Semi-Auto Pistol that one can count on in an emergency.

postcontent: The Polish P64 was the Communists' answer to small caliber sidearms for police and military personnel during the Cold War. In order to prevent NATO forces from seizing weapons caches in the event of a war, the Russians developed the 9x18 or 9mm Makarov. This pistol is chambered in that round, and has most likely seen use with Polish police forces prior to being imported here in the United States. Despite its signs of wear, it is a great versatile pistol. Makes the perfect beater/truck gun or if you enjoy collecting Commie Bloc firearms.
